E. COLI EHEC - USA (06): (KANSAS), HUS CLUSTER, O157
****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat May 2014
Source: KCTV [edited]
http://www.kctv5.com/story/25544933/four-people-in-kansas-diagnosed-with-rare-disorder


A potentially deadly disease has popped up in the Kansas City metro. Recently, there have been 3 cases of hemolytic uremic syndrome, or HUS, diagnosed and treated in Wichita, KS, and now one in Kansas City. HUS is most commonly contracted by eating contaminated foods.

One 20-year-old woman, from Kansas City, who got the disease arrived home after an unexpected extended stay in Texas. What she had was caused by an infection with a certain strain of _E. coli_ [O157:H7] that then prematurely kills red blood cells and can cause kidney failure.

The woman believes she may have come into contact with _E. coli_ from eating a deli sandwich. She began feeling sick several weeks ago, but it didn't get serious until a trip to Texas, where she was then hospitalized.

"It's really scary, because I didn't know what was going on, and all I knew was when you deal with dialysis and transfusions, you're dealing with something pretty heavy duty, and it was scary," said her stepfather.

[Byline: Laura McCallister, Nathan Vickers, Chris Oberholtz]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The report of a cluster of HUS cases should reflect a larger outbreak of EHEC infection, as only between 5-10 percent of cases of EHEC develop HUS, with a higher risk in small children.

It is worrisome that EHEC clusters have occurred in Michigan, apparently in Ohio, and now in Kansas, all states in the Midwestern parts of the USA. It is alleged in unofficial sources that some of the Michigan cases and the Ohio cases are genetically linked. It is possible that many of these cases are part of a common vehicle outbreak. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2480539,219.]
